-Evolution of Cloud Computing-
1.)Physical Servers
Organizations initially relied on dedicated physical servers for each application. This required large data centers, expensive hardware, and significant maintenance.

2.)Virtualization
Virtualization technology allowed multiple virtual machines to run on a single physical server, improving resource efficiency and reducing hardware costs.

3.)Automation & Remote Management
Tools were developed to automate server deployment and management remotely, reducing manual configuration and improving scalability.

4.)Cloud Computing Platforms
Companies like Amazon Web Services introduced on-demand infrastructure, allowing businesses to instantly deploy computing resources without owning physical hardware.

5.)Modern Cloud Computing
Today, organizations can build globally accessible, highly scalable applications using cloud platforms.

-Key Benefits of Cloud Computing-

1.)On-Demand Resources – Businesses can create or remove computing instances instantly without waiting for hardware.

2.)Scalability – Infrastructure can grow or shrink depending on demand.

3.)Cost Efficiency – Organizations only pay for the resources they use.

4.)High Security Standards – Major cloud providers invest heavily in security infrastructure.

5.)High Availability – Applications can remain online even if individual servers fail.

6.)Global Access – Services can be deployed across multiple regions worldwide.

-Types of Cloud Deployment Models-
1.)Public Cloud

Cloud resources are owned and managed by third-party providers.
Commonly used by startups, web platforms, and global applications due to low cost and easy scalability.

2.)Private Cloud

Infrastructure dedicated to a single organization.
Common in industries like banking, healthcare, and government where compliance and data control are critical.

3.)Hybrid Cloud

Combines public and private cloud infrastructure.
Often used by large organizations (such as e-commerce companies) to keep sensitive data private while scaling workloads publicly during high demand.

-Cloud Service Models-
1.)Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)

-Users rent basic computing resources such as virtual machines, storage, and networking.
-The provider manages the physical infrastructure while the user manages the operating system and applications.

2.)Platform as a Service (PaaS)

-The cloud provider manages the infrastructure and operating system.
-Developers focus on building and deploying applications without managing servers.

3.)Software as a Service (SaaS)

-Complete applications delivered through the internet.
-Users simply access the software through a browser or app while the provider manages everything.
-Examples include services like Gmail and Zoom.

